{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477382"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:00:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:00:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14511"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14511"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.11,0.2,0.14,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7206"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108901"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7206"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14511"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91268"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"318"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4034"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18041"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34601"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40508"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108901"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of fever and rash. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 190/min, blood pressure 65/35 mmHg, respiratory rate 40/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. He weighs 10 kg. A widespread petechial rash is visible on his trunk and extremities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial intravenous fluid management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["20 mL/hour of 0.9% saline","40 mL/hour of 0.18% saline with 4% glucose","40 mL/hour of 0.9% saline","200 mL bolus of 0.18% saline with 4% glucose","100 mL bolus of 0.9% saline"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with signs of shock (tachycardia and hypotension) in the context of fever and a petechial rash, likely due to sepsis. The most appropriate initial management is fluid resuscitation with isotonic crystalloids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E100 mL bolus of 0.9% saline\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer. In paediatric shock, the recommended initial fluid bolus is 10-20 mL/kg of isotonic crystalloid (such as 0.9% saline). For this 10 kg infant, that equates to 100 mL. This rapid fluid administration aims to improve tissue perfusion and haemodynamic status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E20 mL/hour of 0.9% saline\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E40 mL/hour of 0.9% saline\u003C/strong\u003E are both insufficient for initial resuscitation in shock. These rates are more appropriate for maintenance fluids, which should only be considered after initial resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E40 mL/hour of 0.18% saline with 4% glucose\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E200 mL bolus of 0.18% saline with 4% glucose\u003C/strong\u003E are inappropriate for initial management of shock. Hypotonic solutions like 0.18% saline should not be used for fluid resuscitation as they can worsen hyponatraemia and cerebral oedema. Additionally, glucose-containing solutions are not recommended for initial fluid resuscitation in shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the initial bolus, the patient should be reassessed. If signs of shock persist, additional boluses may be given. Once the patient is haemodynamically stable, maintenance fluids can be considered. Maintenance fluids for a 10 kg child would typically be calculated using the 4-2-1 rule: (4 x 10) + (2 x 0) + (1 x 0) = 40 mL/hour. However, in the acute setting of potential sepsis, fluid management should be tailored to the patient\u0027s clinical status and response to treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while addressing the fluid status, other aspects of sepsis management should also be initiated, including obtaining cultures, starting empiric antibiotics, and providing supportive care as needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Initial fluid resuscitation in a febrile infant with signs of shock should be with isotonic crystalloids such as 0.9% saline.","The recommended initial bolus volume for fluid resuscitation in paediatric shock is 10-20 mL/kg.","Maintenance fluids are typically calculated using the 4-2-1 rule, but should not be the first step in managing shock."],"references":["Kight BP, Waseem M. Pediatric Fluid Management. [Updated 2023 Feb 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560540/","Starship Children\u0027s Health. Intravenous fluids. Starship Clinical Guidelines. Available from: https://starship.org.nz/guidelines/intravenous-fluids/","Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Resuscitation: Care of the seriously unwell child [Internet]. Melbourne: Royal Children\u0027s Hospital; [cited 2025 Jul 14]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Resuscitation__Care_of_the_seriously_unwell_child/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91268"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14511"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91268"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-14T18:40:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-14T18:41:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7206"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108901"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"